.TH ziptool 1 "Linux tools for Iomega JAZ and ZIP drives Version 1.1" \" -*- nroff -*-
.SH NAME
jaztool, ziptool \- Tool for Iomega JAZ and ZIP drives
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B jaztool
option device [mountdir]
.br
.B ziptool
option device [mountdir]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Disk write-protection is done by software for Iomega's JAZ and ZIP drives.
.BR jaztool
and
.BR ziptool
make these features available for Linux. Before performing any protection
mode changes, it is checked that
.I device
is actually a JAZ or ZIP drive and that no partition of the inserted disk
is currently mounted.
.PP
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
.TP 8
.B \-e
Eject the disk.
.TP 8
.B \-ro
Make disk read\-only. If the current mode is protected by a password, you
are prompted for it.
.TP 8
.B \-rp
Make disk read\-only and protect this mode with a password. The maximum
length of a password is 33 characters.
.RS
.PP
.B WARNING:
Don't forget the password! Otherwise you will have to reformat the disk
in order to remove write\-protection.
.RE
.TP 8
.B \-rw
Remove any protection from the disk. If the current mode is protected by
a password, you are prompted for it.
.TP 8
.B \-ld
Lock the Drive door so the disk cannot be ejected.  Only works if the disk
is already mounted.
.TP 8
.B \-ud
Unlock the Drive door
.TP 8
.B \-m
Mount the device dev4 on [dir], then lock the door (like -ld)
.TP 8
.B \-u 
Unmount the device dev4.
.TP 8
.B \-s
Get the current protection status. Supported modes are:
.RS
.IP
unprotected
.br
write-protected
.br
password write-protected
.RE
.SH BUGS
Changing password if the disk is password write-protected is
currently not supported. If you want to change the password now you
first have to remove protection from the disk or put it into the
write protected mode and after that switch it back to password
write-protected mode.
.PP
Not all protection modes offered by the JAZ and ZIP drives can be
supported under Linux (i.e. password read and write-protected mode).
.SH AUTHOR
Mirko Kraft (Mirko.Kraft@ixos.de)
.br
